4Ô∏è‚É£ What is a System Call?

A system call is the mechanism through which a user-space program requests a service from the kernel.

User programs cannot directly access hardware or kernel memory. Instead, they use system calls as a controlled interface.

Examples:

open() ‚Üí open file

read() ‚Üí read data

write() ‚Üí write data

fork() ‚Üí create new process

exec() ‚Üí execute program

System calls ensure secure communication between user space and kernel space.

In simple words:
System call = Gateway from user space to kernel space.

5Ô∏è‚É£ What is User Space vs Kernel Space?
User Space

This is where applications and user programs run.
It has limited privileges and cannot directly access hardware.

Examples:

nginx

docker

vim

python scripts

If an application crashes in user space, the system continues running.

Kernel Space

This is where the Linux kernel operates.
It has full access to hardware and system memory.

Responsibilities:

Process scheduling

Memory allocation

Device drivers

Networking stack

File systems

If a problem occurs in kernel space, it can crash the entire system.

6Ô∏è‚É£ What happens when you run a command like ls?

When you type ls, the following sequence happens:

The shell reads the command.

It searches for the executable in directories listed in the PATH variable.

Once found (e.g., /bin/ls), it loads the program into memory.

The program makes system calls like:

open()

read()

The kernel processes these system calls and retrieves directory data.

The output is sent back to user space.

The shell prints the result to the terminal.

Flow:

User ‚Üí Shell ‚Üí System Call ‚Üí Kernel ‚Üí Hardware ‚Üí Output

This answer is very commonly asked in interviews.

4Ô∏è‚É£ System Libraries
üîπ English Explanation

System libraries are pre-written code helpers.

Applications use them to:

Talk to kernel

Avoid writing low-level code

Example:

glibc

üîπ Real-Time Example

When a program needs memory:
üëâ It calls library
üëâ Library calls kernel

üîπ Interview Points

Libraries provide APIs

Bridge between apps & kernel

üîπ Telugu Explanation

System libraries ante ready-made helper code

Apps direct ga kernel ni touch cheyavu
üëâ Library use chesi matladutayi

5Ô∏è‚É£ Applications / User Space

This is where users work.
Includes:
Terminal
Browser
Docker
Jenkins
Kubernetes tools
Apps never directly access hardware.

Architecture full explanation:
Linux architecture follows a layered model. The user interacts with the system through the shell by running commands. 
These commands invoke user-space utilities, which use system libraries like glibc. 
The libraries internally make system calls to request services from the kernel. 
The kernel, being the core of Linux, manages processes, memory, files, devices, networking, and communicates directly with the hardware.

