5) Kernel vs Shell
| Feature          | Kernel       | Shell      |
| ---------------- | ------------ | ---------- |
| Role             | Core of OS   | Interface  |
| Runs in          | Kernel space | User space |
| Hardware access  | Yes          | No         |
| User interaction | No           | Yes        |
| Crash impact     | Whole system | Only shell |
| Examples         | Process mgmt | bash, zsh  |

7) What is Linux File System?

Linux File System is a hierarchical structure used by the Linux OS to organize, store, retrieve, and manage data on storage devices. It follows a single-rooted tree structure starting from / (root directory).

| Directory | Purpose              | DevOps Use Case    |
| --------- | -------------------- | ------------------ |
| `/`       | Root directory       | Starting point     |
| `/bin`    | Essential binaries   | `ls`, `cp`, `mv`   |
| `/etc`    | Configuration files  | Nginx, SSH configs |
| `/var`    | Logs & variable data | App logs           |
| `/home`   | User directories     | Dev user files     |
| `/tmp`    | Temporary files      | Build temp files   |
| `/opt`    | Optional software    | Custom apps        |
| `/usr`    | User programs        | Installed packages |
| `/dev`    | Device files         | Disk devices       |
| `/proc`   | Process info         | Runtime info       |

7.1)File Types in Linux

| Symbol | Type             |
| ------ | ---------------- |
| `-`    | Regular file     |
| `d`    | Directory        |
| `l`    | Symbolic link    |
| `c`    | Character device |
| `b`    | Block device     |
| `s`    | Socket           |
| `p`    | Named pipe       |

7.2) What is an Inode?

An inode is a data structure that stores metadata about a file, but NOT the file name.
It contains:
File size
Owner
Permissions
Timestamps
Disk block location

7.3) Hard Link vs Soft Link
üîó Hard Link
Points to same inode
Cannot cross filesystem
Cannot link directory

ln file1 file2

üîó Soft Link (Symbolic Link)

Points to filename path
Can cross filesystem
Can link directory

ln -s file1 symlink

7.4) Difference between hard link and soft link?

| Hard Link                            | Soft Link                  |
| ------------------------------------ | -------------------------- |
| Same inode                           | Different inode            |
| Cannot cross filesystem              | Can cross filesystem       |
| File exists even if original deleted | Broken if original deleted |
